I started this #plaidishquilt last year. Made 2 blocks and then it went into hibernation. I pulled everything out the other day and devoted a day and a half to cutting, making blocks and getting the quilt top put together!  I just picked it up from my quilter and am excited to have something Christmasy to bind when I get a few moments here and there over the next couple of weeks. My little quilt group and I are doing a block swap. Does anyone know what one of these blocks is called (this is 9 blocks sewn together)? Half of us are doing earthy colors and the other half are doing black and white prints (two different swaps). I’m in the earthy group and it’s a good study on what earthy colors are. When I think of earth tones I think of muddy colors, colors with gray or black undertones, colors you would see in nature - specifically in the fall or winter. It’s fun thinking, “Oh I would see that color in a pond, a field, a sunset, a mountain, etc.”

Here are a few cutting tips to help things go a little faster:

I saw a quilt like this at my friend’s mom’s house recently and knew I wanted to make one too. Super scrappy and simple. Mindless sewing for the win!  Just sew together 4-1/2” wide scraps in varying lengths into one long strip. Press the seams open and then cut the strip into 4-1/2” segments. Rotate the segments so the strips alternate directions; sew together in rows and press. 

I’m doing an 18 x 21 layout to make a quilt about 72” x 84”. Im figuring I need a strip of about 142 feet of scraps.

It’s week 11 of the Positive Vibes QAL. Time to assemble all the rows!  First, lay out your blocks. Spread out like colors and prints to create balance. 

Tip: take a photo with your phone, adjust the saturation to zero to see where the bold fabrics are. Move them if necessary to create balance. 

Stack up the blocks in each diagonal row (start left to right, left block on top; adjacent blocks underneath). Number each row to keep everything in order. Make 10 block rows and 11 sashing rows according to the quilt diagram in the pattern. 

Next week we’ll sew the rows together to make our quilt top. Yay!

Let’s tie a quilter’s knot!  First, thread your needle. Continue to pull the thread through the eye of the needle about 3-4 inches to create a short piece of thread and a long piece of thread on either side of the needle. Wrap the end of the long piece of thread around the needle - 3 times. Grab the 3 “wraps” between your thumb and pointer finger and gently slide them off the needle. Keep sliding them until they create a knot at the end of the long piece of thread. Be careful not to let go of the “wraps” or let the thread tangle. 

Do you tie your quilting/appliqué stitching knots like this?
